 culture at different moments in our history. Until the 1970s, Canadians framed their grievances with reference to Christianity or British justice rather than human rights. A historical sociological approach to human rights reveals how rights are historically contingent, and how new rights claims are built upon past claims. This book explores governments’ tendency to suppress rights in periods of perceived emergency; how Canada’s rights culture was shaped by state formation; how social movements have advanced new rights claims; the changing discourse of rights in debates surrounding the constitution; how the international human rights movement shaped domestic politics and foreign policy; and much more. In addition to drawing on secondary literature in law, history, sociology, and political science, this study looked to published government documents, litigation and case law, archival research, newspapers, opinion polls, and materials produced by non-governmental organizations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDroits de l'homme (Droit international)xHistoirexCanadaxCanada. 0aHuman rightsxHistoryxCanada. 0aHuman rightsxSocial aspectsxCanada. 0aHuman rightsxSocial aspectszCanada. 0aHuman rightszCanadaxHistory. 4aHistory: Canadian History. 4aPolitical Science: Social Policy. 4aSocial Science: Sociology. 7aHISTORY / Social History.2bisacsh  aAboriginal peoples.  aCharter of Rights and Freedoms.  aConfederation.  aGouzenko.  aOctober Crisis.  aRebellions.  aWWI and WWII.  acanada.  acivil liberties.  adiscrimination.  aemergencies.  aforeign policy.  ahuman rights.  ainternational human rights.  alabour.  alaw.  apolitics.  areligion.  asex discrimination.  asexual orientation.  asocial movements.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complet